  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law intersects with national laws on money laundering through several key mechanisms and frameworks:\n\n1. Global Standards and Recommendations\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) sets international standards\n- Provides guidelines for national anti-money laundering (AML) regulations\n- Develops recommendations for legal and regulatory approaches\n\n2. International Cooperation Mechanisms\n- Mutual Legal Assistance Treaties (MLATs)\n- Information sharing between financial intelligence units\n- Extradition agreements for money laundering prosecutions\n\n3. United Nations Conventions\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- UN Convention against Corruption\n- Provide legal frameworks for international cooperation\n\n4. Compliance Requirements\n- Banks and financial institutions must implement cross-border AML protocols\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) and Customer Due Diligence (CDD) standards\n- Reporting suspicious transactions internationally\n\n5. Enforcement Coordination\n- Joint investigations\n- Asset tracing and recovery\n- Coordinated legal actions across jurisdictions\n\n6. Regulatory Harmonization\n- Encouraging consistent legal approaches\n- Aligning national legislation with international standards\n- Creating more robust global anti-money laundering frameworks\n\nThese intersections help create comprehensive strategies to combat financial crimes globally.",
